title: For Sale:  Arisaka type 38
postcontent: I have a relatively good condition example of a Japanese WWII service rifle, it is all matching and the bore is in excellent shape.  Unfortunately, like most Japanese rifles at the end of WWII, the bayonet lug and Chrysanthemum were ground off.  This was done by Japanese troops before surrendering their weapons, because the Chrysanthemum and bayonet lug marked the rifle as the personal property of the Emperor.  By grinding these two things off, the Japanese troops could keep their honor intact.  It is a wonderful piece of history and the cheapest you will ever find one.

MD Criminal Law Article §4-201
(b) Antique firearm. -- "Antique firearm" means:

(1) a firearm, including a firearm with a matchlock, flintlock, percussion cap, or similar ignition system, manufactured before 1899; or

(2) a replica of a firearm described in item (1) of this subsection that: (i) is not designed or redesigned to use rimfire or conventional centerfire fixed ammunition; or (ii) uses rimfire or conventional centerfire fixed ammunition that is no longer manufactured in the United States and is not readily available in the ordinary channels of commercial trade

 (c)      (1)      "Handgun" means a pistol, revolver, or other firearm capable of being concealed on the person.
            (2)      "Handgun" includes a short-barreled shotgun and a short-barreled rifle.
            (3)      "Handgun" does not include a shotgun, rifle, or antique firearm.

title: For Sale:  RARE:  EAGLE Ruger Mini-30 magazine
postcontent:
EAGLE magazines are the only magazine made with a constant tension spring.  The first and last rounds have the same force against the bottom of the rifle’s bolt.  In a typical high capacity magazine, the coil spring occupies the bottom 20% of the magazine, wasted space.  With an EAGLE, a constant-tension, rolled-ribbon spring hangs from the top, allowing ammo to be loaded to the absolute bottom of the magazine (no wasted space hanging down).  These magazines have the strongest plastic of any magazine, and window-glass clear so you can see exactly how many rounds are loaded.  This is the best built magazine, ever, rock-solid strong.  Unfortunately, they were discontinued with the Clinton magazine ban.

EAGLEs are the smoothest functioning magazine ever made.  I love them.  This one (for a Ruger Mini-30) was accidentally included in a large dealer order, back, in about 1990.  I’ve sold 100’s of these for Mini-14 without a single complaint.  

See and own this unique, wonderful magazine.  Be the lucky one who gets this jewel for only $10, new in factory-sealed-blister-pack.

I have only one for Ruger Mini-30.  The others in the photo are similar examples (for Ruger Mini-14), and not for sale.
